Saturday, December 2020

Today was a very special day for those who believed in deities.

A very, very special day.

Jack had prepared for this occasion with far more thoroughness than last year's celebration. The decorations at the headquarters, including the pine tree he had dragged out of the warehouse residue, were all recycled from the previous year. However, their arrangement was much more optimal this time.

Even so, the room still felt suffocatingly empty.

Every breath Jack took was laced with the synthetic, plasticky smell of old decorations, used only once a year. He had no idea how much dust would have settled on them if he had simply chosen to forget.

And perhaps it would have been better, if he could just forget entire years at a time.

He pulled out the box where he kept his vinyl records. Inside were famous albums spanning from the 1970s to 2019. There was Dedicated to Markos III, which Jack preferred to call "Black Flower", all the way to the High School Musical soundtrack, his family's favorite during past Christmases.

He picked out the High School Musical soundtrack, specifically choosing the song "All I Want," released in 2019.
The blue-and-white, beach-themed vinyl cover, featuring a woman sitting at a piano, was exactly the same as he remembered. Even the song itself hadn't changed.

He slid the record out of its sleeve, placed it onto the brand-new headquarters gramophone, and dropped the needle, giving the sound a distinct, unfamiliar texture he couldn’t quite name.

The chorus and the refrain didn’t shift a single note.

Neither did his memories.

Unlike the vinyl spinning on the platter, Jack's family had changed completely. They were living their own lives now, choosing their own paths.

The warmth of that memory was gone, leaving only the cold reality of the headquarters. The delicate, acoustic notes of the song pulsed through the empty room, sounding more like a funeral march for his past than a holiday celebration. Jack closed his eyes, letting his carbon-fiber hands rest flat against the cold metal table, completely drowning in the static of things he couldn't delete.

He looked at his carbon-fiber hands resting on the metal table which were still scratched from the incident last month. The red patterns surrounding the bandages slicks, like abstract patterns that are not full of meaning. Everything felt like it was spinning too fast. Jack couldn't tell if he was the one speeding things up or if it was just a distraction.

The sting was still the same. Under the bandages that were starting to peel, the water from when he first touched them was still there, he didn't regret his previous choice. Well, if only he hadn't met him.

Jack's feelings of uncertainty about "him" also didn't change. Didn't care if the days have gone by until it have become months.

The high-pitched, melancholic hum of Olivia’s voice cut through the plastic-scented air. It was a melody that used to mean safety, a domestic warmth shared under a far friendlier roof.
Now, it just sounded like an echo in an abandoned tomb.

Jack didn't even hear the heavy, metallic thud of the headquarters' secondary door sliding open. He was too busy staring at the flickering, recycled Christmas lights reflecting off his carbon-fiber knuckles.

"A bit too tragic for a holy night, don't you think, Blondie? Look at you, wallowing in your own pathetic shit like a broken toy."

The voice was rough, dripping with that unbearable Brazilian cadence that Jack had learned to both loathe and crave. He stood at the edge of the hallway, a dusting of white snow melting rapidly against his dark, heavy cybernetic chassis. He didn't look like he belonged anywhere near a pine tree. He looked like an intruder in a memory.

Before Jack could snap a retort or reach for his blade, the man closed the distance. His movements were fluid and careless, completely ignoring the tense, defensive shift in Jack’s shoulders.

"Turn that frown upside down, Jackass. If you're going to mourn a ghost, at least do it with some rhythm," he chuckled, his massive hand suddenly coming down to capture Jack’s left wrist.

With a mock-gallant sweep, he pulled Jack closer, forcing him into a slow, clumsy sway right in the middle of the cold metal floor.

"Let's dance."

It was a dance. A horrible, distorted slow dance.

The contrast was sickening. The delicate, acoustic notes of "All I Want" pulsed through the room, while beneath Jack's palm, he could feel the low, aggressive hum of the man’s internal exoskeleton fan, while his wrist still hurt the most.

Jack’s right hand instinctively went to his shoulder to keep his balance, but his mind instantly short-circuited. The height difference, the weight of the hand pressing firmly against his lower back, the way his ponytail swayed slightly with their movements...

It was horribly, grossly familiar.

He had stood like this before. Years ago. In a sterile apartment, holding a woman who actually looked at him with tenderness instead of bloodlust.

She thinks it's special.

Then, it's all reused.

"You're stiff," the man murmured, his breath hot against the side of Jack's jaw, right near the fragile film seal. "Am I bringing back bad memories, pretty boy?"

Jack forced a sharp snort, trying to steady his erratic pulse before his internal monitors could blare a warning to the Doctor in the other room. He tightened his grip on his shoulder, leaning into the cringey, toxic warmth of the hold. He hated it. He hated how much his broken system wanted this hand to stay right there on his neck.

"Shut up, Sam," Jack whispered, his voice cracking slightly through the vinyl static. "Just... don't stop."

His chuckle vibrated against Jack's collarbone, a low, rumbling frequency that felt entirely too physical to be a glitch. He didn't stop. He guided Jack through another slow turn, their boots scraping against the cold floor in perfect, agonizing sync with Olivia's high-pitched voice.

"Tell me, Blondie," the man murmured, his fingers tracing the sensitive wires under Jack’s jaw with a sickening familiarity. "Does she know you're doing this? The little housewife? Did you dance with her under this exact same plastic piece of garbage, or did you just freeze up like a fucking coward back then too?"

Jack didn't answer.

He couldn't.

Because the terrifying truth was, he had.
The choreography was identical. The way his left hand rested on a heavy shoulder, the way his body tilted to compensate for the height difference, it was all a cheap, dirty copy. Jack was recycling the exact same domestic affection he used to give his wife, but now he was serving it to the ghost of the man who had tried to slice his throat open in the badlands.

"Do you get déjà vu, Jackass?" The man’s grin was visible in the reflection of the dark window, sharp and mocking. "Every time you look at the Christmas lights? Every time a song plays? Do you call her name when you're dreaming, or do you call mine?"

Jack tightened his grip on his exoskeleton shoulder, his carbon-fiber fingers denting the phantom metal. Strangely, beneath his palm, his armor didn't feel cold like the winter storm outside. It felt warm. Exactly as warm as Jack's own internal generator.

And whenever they turned past the recycled Christmas lights, the man's shadow on the wall didn't seem to match his movements. It stayed completely still, broad and towering, while Jack was the only one casting a frantic, swaying silhouette against the floor.

"Shut up," Jack hissed, closing his eyes to block out the tearing pixels of his face.

He leaned deeper into the hold, chasing the heavy, phantom weight on his lower back. He hated how perfectly the nightmare fit. He hated that his brain, desperate for any shred of warmth in this abandoned tomb of a headquarters, had cross-wired his memories of love with his addiction to a ghost.

The vinyl skipped.

The melody settled, quiet and brutal.

Outside, December howled in white.

Inside, Jack kept dancing.

A glitching brain, erasing the lines.
Blurring the real.

Chasing the phantom.
